The best way to handle this problem is to handle the source data before it ever gets written to file. `&quot;@{Phone: iPhone; Computer: Mac}&quot;` in a CSV file is not ideal. It seems like that data was manipulated before exported to CSV and having that in a different format would make this problem a lot simpler.

Working with what is available, you can do the following:

    $obj = @&quot;
    Name;Age;Devices
    Peter;20;&quot;@{Phone: iPhone; Computer: Mac}&quot;
    Lisa;22;&quot;@{Phone: Samsung; Computer: HP}&quot;
    &quot;@ | ConvertFrom-Csv -Delimiter &#39;;&#39;
    
    $output = foreach ($o in $obj) {
        $hash = $o.Devices -replace &#39;[@{}]&#39; -replace &#39;:&#39;,&#39;=&#39; -split &#39;;\s*&#39; | ConvertFrom-StringData
        $hash[0].GetEnumerator() | Foreach-Object {
            $k1 = $_.key
            $v1 = $_.value
        }
        $hash[1].GetEnumerator() | Foreach-Object {
            $k2 = $_.key
            $v2 = $_.value
        }
        $o | Select-Object Name,Age,Devices,@{n=$k1;e={$v1}},@{n=$k2;e={$v2}}
    }
    
    $output | Export-Csv Output.csv -NoTypeInformation -Delimiter &#39;;&#39;

**Explanation:**

When you pipe an object into `Select-Object`, you can calculate new properties that don&#39;t belong to the piped object. Your stringified hashtable data is converted into a hash table using the code above. String manipulation using `-replace` set up the string to be piped into `ConvertFrom-StringData`, which results in a hash table. From that hash table, key-value pairs (`$k` variables and `$v` variables) are created so they can easily be consumed in the `Select-Object` calculated properties.

