I hope you find this answer &quot;somewhat helpful.&quot;  I say &quot;somewhat&quot; primarily because I cannot provide a full answer to your predicament since I have not worked through the Selenium WebDriver library.  I have personally coded a rather large HTML parser for searching and scraping HTML pages.  The reality of the Java Libraries - the libraries included in Java Releases from Sun Micro-Systems - is that there is no &quot;Java Script Execution Library&quot; included.  The &quot;ScriptEngineManager,&quot; is actually a package that I have never used before.  In my defense, there are myriad of extra libraries in the Java Framework that I have no coded.  

What is relevant, though, is that I have done extensive work on parsing, searching and scraping HTML, CSS, Java-Script, AJAX into a Java Library.  You may look at it here, and it has a similar goal to a project called &quot;JSoup&quot; - which has been around for quite a bit longer, however lacks some of my features.  (JSoup Scrape Link: [JSoup.org][1], and Torello.HTML: [developer.torello.directory][2])


  [1]: https://jsoup.org/
  [2]: http://developer.torello.directory/JavaHTML/index.html


The help I can provide is that you need to think about the goal of your project (which isn&#39;t so well elucidated by your question!) - in order to decide which of these additional libraries you want to use.

If you want to actually start executing JavaScript (which I don&#39;t recommend, unless you absolutely have to), you need to review the &quot;Selenium Web Driver Libraries.&quot;  This library is an order of magnitude more complicated, and generally, if you are just trying to obtain a few pieces of data from a website, then going with a simple scrape package, or a hybrid where you make Java Calls and sort of &quot;simulate&quot; AJAX and JSON calls to the webserver is the right idea.  Generally, the Selenium crowd from what I have seen on SO is usually more interested in automated posting and interacting with WebSites, which is what necessitates using the Selenium Java-Script execution libraries.

